<worksheet xml:id="activities-countable">

<activity>
<!-- \label{EXER::same.size} -->
	<introduction><p>
		In each of the following, prove that the given set is countable by exhibiting an explicitly defined bijective correspondence between it and <m>\N</m>.
	</p></introduction>
	<task><p> The set of natural numbers excluding 0. </p></task>
	<task><p> The set of natural numbers that are greater than <m>9,999,999</m>. </p></task>
	<task><p> The set of odd natural numbers. </p></task>
	<task><p> The set of integer powers of <m>2</m> (including both positive and negative exponents). </p></task>
</activity>

<activity xml:id="activity-countable-same-size-or-subset-of-countable">
<!-- \label{EXER::same.size.or.subset.of.countable} -->
	<introduction>
		<p>
		Without cheating and looking at the proofs in this chapter,
		prove each of the following statements.
		You may wish to make use of the characterization of countability in
		<xref ref="fact-countable-infinite-iff-seq" />
		instead of the technical definition of <term>countable set</term>.
		</p><p>
		<em>Note:</em> Each statement except the first two can be proved directly from the preceding statements.
		</p>
	</introduction>
	<task><p> Every subset of <m>\N</m> is countable. </p></task>
	<task><p> If two sets have the same size and one of them is countable, then so is the other. </p></task>
	<task><p> Every set that is the same size as a subset of <m>\N</m> is countable. </p></task>
	<task><p> Every subset of a countable set is countable. </p></task>
	<task><p> Every set that is the same size as a subset of a countable set is countable. </p></task>
	<task><p> A set that contains an uncountable subset is uncountable. </p></task>
</activity>

<activity xml:id="activity-countable-product-of-countable">
<!-- \label{EXER::product.of.countable} -->
	<task xml:id="activity-countable-product-of-countable-naturals">
		<statement><p> Prove that <m>\N \times \N</m> is countable. </p></statement>
		<hint><p>
			Use a zig-zag-through-a-grid method similar to the proof of the countability of the rational numbers.
			(See <xref ref="theorem-countable-integers-rationals" /> and its proof.)
		</p></hint>
	</task>
	<task xml:id="activity-countable-product-of-countable-general-two">
		<statement><p> Prove that if <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are both countable, then so is <m>A \times B</m>. </p></statement>
		<hint><p>
			You could do more zig-zagging, or you could use the statement of
			<xref ref="activity-countable-product-of-countable-naturals" text="type-local" />.
		</p></hint>
	</task>
	<task>
		<statement><p> Prove that if <m>X</m>, <m>Y</m>, and <m>Z</m> are each countable, then so is <m>X \times Y \times Z</m>. </p></statement>
		<hint><p> Use the statement of <xref ref="activity-countable-product-of-countable-general-two" text="type-local" /> twice. </p></hint>
	</task>
	<task>
		<p> What proof method do you think you would use to prove the following statement? </p>
		<blockquote><p> If <m>A_1, A_2, \dotsc, A_n</m> are all countable, then so is <me> A_1\times A_2 \times \dotsb \times A_n </me>. </p></blockquote>
	</task>
</activity>

<activity><title>The Infinite Orchard Problem</title><p>
	You own a magical apple orchard that contains an infinite number of trees, each of which bears an infinite number of apples.
	Describe a method to pick all of the apples in the orchard, <alert>one apple at a time</alert>.
	(No shaking the trees, please! However, you may assume an infinite amount of time.)
</p></activity>

<activity>
	<statement><p>
		Prove that if <m>A_0,A_1,A_2,\dotsc</m> is an infinite collection of sets, each of which is countably infinite,
		then the union
		<me> \bigcup_{n=0}^\infty A_n = A_0 \cup A_1 \cup A_2 \cup \dotsb </me>
		is also countably infinite.
	</p></statement>
	<hint><p> What if each set was an apple tree? </p></hint>
</activity>

<activity xml:id="activity-countable-functions-binary-domain">
	<introduction><p> Let <m>\mathscr{F}</m> represent the set of all functions with domain <m>\{0,1\}</m> and codomain <m>\N</m>. </p></introduction>
	<task xml:id="activity-countable-functions-binary-domain-bij"><p>
		Determine a bijective correspondence between <m>\mathscr{F}</m> and <m>\N \times \N</m>.
	</p></task>
	<task>
		<statement><p>
			Explain why
			<xref ref="activity-countable-functions-binary-domain-bij" text="type-local" />
			proves that <m>\mathscr{F}</m> is countable.
		</p></statement>
		<hint><p>
			See <xref ref="activity-countable-same-size-or-subset-of-countable" />
			and <xref ref="activity-countable-product-of-countable" />.
		</p></hint>
	</task>
</activity>

<activity xml:id="activity-countable-functions-binary-codomain">
	<introduction>
		<p> Let <m>\mathscr{F}'</m> represent the set of all functions with domain <m>\N</m> and codomain <m>\{0,1\}</m>. </p>
		<p> Note that each element of <m>\mathscr{F}'</m> defines an infinite sequence of <m>0</m>s and <m>1</m>s. </p>
	</introduction>
	<task xml:id="activity-countable-functions-binary-codomain-countable-proper">
		<statement>
			<p>
			Suppose <m>A</m> is a countable subset of <m>\mathscr{F}'</m>.
			(So <m>A</m> is an infinite list of infinite sequences of <m>0</m>s and <m>1</m>s.)
			</p><p>
			Describe how to construct an element of <m>\mathscr{F}'</m> that is definitely not in <m>A</m>.
			That is, build an infinite sequence of <m>0</m>s and <m>1</m>s that is definitely not the same as any of the infinite sequences in the infinite list of <m>A</m>.
			</p>
		</statement>
		<hint><p> Use Cantor's diagonal argument from the proof of <xref ref="lemma-countable-uncountable-subset-of-reals" />. </p></hint>
	</task>
	<task>
		<statement><p>
			Explain why <xref ref="activity-countable-functions-binary-codomain-countable-proper" text="type-local" />
			proves that <m>\mathscr{F}'</m> is uncountable.
		</p></statement>
		<hint><p> <m>\mathscr{F}' \subseteq \mathscr{F}'</m>. </p></hint>
	</task>
</activity>

</worksheet>
